<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Dawn of Inferno</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The sands of time have run out.  The shadow that has fallen upon Norrath now recedes.  The age dwindles and falls, claiming with it another civilization to conflict.  As mortal armies rush blindly towards defeat, the Burning Prince comes to consume all.  The heretics shall fall before His wrath.  The followers shall fall upon fools.  And His spear shall be lifted unto the heavens and all of Norrath will tremble before His burning power.  The echoes of war shall sound throughout the land and all of Norrath shall be consumed in a never-ending inferno.  Thus will the Age of Flame begin.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The War of Faydwer</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
It was that time of year again.  That time always came.  Possibly one of the few times the Koada'Dal and Feir'Dal put aside their pride.  For a week, the gnomes and dwarves were not seen as inferiors, but as friends.  It was the single time of year where the average elf could treat a gnome or dwarf with respect without an awkward sense.  It was time to celebrate Tunare.  All the believers reveled in the days of celebration, and on the last evening of the festivities, all the non-believers were invited to come.  The idea was to try to convert them.  Although, truth be told, the gnomes just turned out for the women, and the dwarves the ale.  <br>
<br>
Ikeya grimaced.  It was his least favorite time of the year.  The paladins would round up all the local non-believers and lock them up in one of the inns and not let them out until the last day, for their chance to be converted.  Then there were the gnomes and dwarves; tiny little creatures, running drunkenly around his knees.  Ikeya shuddered at the thought.  It wasn't that he hated gnomes or dwarves; it was just that he hated large groups of them.  Sadly, it always seemed their entire population showed up for the celebration.  Sighing, he opened a scroll and began to read... and wait for the paladins to come and take him away.<br>
<br>
--<br>
<br>
Tearis Thex sat on his throne, his advisors giving details on the upcoming festival.  The paladins would be coming shortly to ask permission to lock the heretics away.  Tearis winced.  Every year there were some new people who converted, but there were always many more who refused to.  He sighed.  The festival was meant to be one of the most joyous times of the year.  Indeed it was; however, the refusal by a few of his brothers to submit to the Mother weighed heavily upon him.  He frowned, remembering one of his brothers, who last year had cursed Tunare's name.  He had shouted that he was a follower of Solusek Ro and would not change his path.  Tearis winced again in mental anguish.  The memories of Takish-Hiz came flooding back to him at the thought of the Burning Prince.  The white marble towers, the trees that lined the streets, the grand forest at the city's edge.  Takish-Hiz was the most beautiful city in all of Norrath... until Solusek Ro destroyed it.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>No, now is not the time to dwell upon the past</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, Tearis thought, shaking his head to clear his mind of the memories.    He looked up and saw the double doors to the room swing open. Marching in was a group of paladins.  Tearis noted that one of them was carrying a scroll.  Waving a hand toward one of his advisors, he beckoned for a quill so he could sign the order granting the paladins the permission they needed to imprison the heretics.<br>
<br>
--<br>
<br>
It was a knock on the door that woke Ikeya up.  He considered not responding, but frowned.  If he didn't respond, the paladins would just enter his home anyway and look for him.  Ikeya focused on the door. It bounced open and slammed against its frame with a loud crack.  The two paladins that had come to take him away were clearly shocked.  Ikeya permitted a smile as he saw their expressions.  After a few seconds, they regained their composure and walked into the room.  <br>
<br>
&quot;We request that you come with us,&quot; one of the paladins said bluntly.  <br>
<br>
Ikeya wrestled with the thought of not acquiescing to the request, but the result was never in doubt.  If he refused, the paladins would just start reciting the annoying order the king signed that gave them permission to collect the 'heretics.'  Ikeya nodded indifferently and stood up, hunching his shoulders to stretch out their stiff muscles.<br>
<br>
&quot;Shall we?&quot; he said politely.  The paladins stood on either side of the door, waiting for him to pass.  He glanced at the soldiers as he walked by, and saw two unfamiliar faces beneath their silver helms.  They had to be new to the order.  He chuckled to himself.  It would explain their reaction to the way he opened his door… after all, he greeted the paladins the same way every year.  The self-satisfying salutation was costly, however, as he had to replace his door each time. <br>
<br>
His smile vanished as the paladins ushered him into the group of heretics waiting outside.  He nodded at the motley crowd.  They were all familiar with each other, though their numbers dwindled each and every year.  Ikeya found it somewhat ironic that the Karana worshippers were also rounded up, seeing as Karana and Tunare were supposedly allies.  Apparently, the feeling of unity didn't extend to their followers... or at least it didn't to that fanatic fool Thex.  As the paladins pushed him into the middle of the group, he saw a face he didn't recognize. <br>
<br>
&quot;So tell me, stranger, what brings you among our rebellious crowd?&quot; Ikeya asked the newcomer, as the group began walking under the watchful gaze of their sentries.<br>
<br>
&quot;My name is Jather.  I've spent the past few hundred years off of Faydwer.  I just came back a few months ago.  It appears my timing was... poor,&quot; the stranger replied.<br>
<br>
&quot;Indeed it was.  They gather all of us up, whether we worship Solusek Ro, Karana, Mithaniel Marr – any of the gods besides Tunare. They just collect us and throw us into an inn for the week.  Not exactly an event I'd say the Koada'Dal should be proud of,&quot; Ikeya concluded softly, lest he attract the attention of one of the high, noble, and easily affronted paladins.  &quot;So tell me, who do you follow?&quot;<br>
<br>
Jather stood up a bit straighter and assumed an aura of pride as he said, &quot;I am a follower of the Burning Prince, Solusek Ro.&quot;  <br>
<br>
Ikeya held back a smile.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Ah... the young and prideful...</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Ikeya thought.  He used to be like Jather.  He was still proud to be a follower of Solusek Ro, of course, but the years of the festivals had taken their toll on him.  His patience was wearing thin.  Not with the festivals themselves, but at the blind passion with which the old king followed Tunare.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah... so there <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>are</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> other followers of the candlestick,&quot; a condescending voice interjected.  &quot;I bet Ikeya is thankful for the company.&quot;<br>
<br>
Jather's head snapped toward the direction of the voice.  Ikeya simply nodded his greetings to Aurianne.  Aurianne was a follower of Karana, and the only reason Ikeya tolerated her was because she was rounded up with the rest of them.  Aurianne tolerated him only because the paladins seemed to make it a point to give him a hard time.  Jather was about to make a retort, but one of the paladins ordered a halt to their march.  <br>
<br>
&quot;You will all be staying here for the week,” the leader called. “Food and drink will be provided daily,&quot; he said as the rest of his men pushed the cluster of elves into the inn.  He slammed the door and continued on his way.  They were only heretics after all.  They didn't warrant his attention.<br>
<br>
--<br>
<br>
Ikeya clapped his hands together, surveying this year’s roundup.  <br>
<br>
“So, what are we going to do for the next six days?” he asked.<br>
<br>
“Nothing that involves you and fire,” someone shouted.  “We’ve destroyed enough inns.”  There was a burst of laughter from the assembly as they remembered the countless times Ikeya or someone else had managed to devastate the inn they had been assigned to.  It was amazing that Felwithe continued the practice, since the cost of containing the so-called “heretics” often rivaled the cost of the festival itself.  The collateral damage was usually extensive.  Locking up wizards and magicians in a tightly compact room wasn’t the best idea to ever come down from the royal court.  On the other hand, the destruction usually paved the way for renovation of a city block.<br>
<br>
“Now, you know the last time wasn’t strictly my fault.  It was Aurianne’s lightning bolt that started that fire,” Ikeya called back with a small smirk.<br>
<br>
“Only because you moved,” Aurianne sneered.  “Had you been gullible enough to stand on the ‘X’ that fire could have been avoided.”<br>
<br>
Ikeya snorted.  <br>
<br>
“Yes… but that doesn’t change the fact that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>you</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> missed.”<br>
<br>
--<br>
<br>
Thex eyed the group of heretics, who stood in a large cluster near the edge of the forest.  The week seemed to go by fast.  It was already the last day of the festival, and the heretics had been brought out.  They seemed to be in good humor this year, which really didn't surprise him.  He wasn't completely oblivious to what happened in Felwithe.  The non-believers had made quite a mess of the inn they had stayed at.  The wine cellar of the inn had exploded and made a mess, to say the least.  They had also managed to set the kitchen on fire.  Thex wasn't entirely sure what they were trying to make, but it obviously hadn’t gone as they had planned.  He grimaced.  Now it was time for him to make his speech to try and convert the heretics... and bring one to punishment.<br>
<br>
One of the followers of Solusek Ro stepped down from the platform.  Her answer after Thex's long and boring speech was the same as it was every year: she would not renounce her loyalty to the Burning Prince.  <br>
<br>
As the king prepared to call the next one forward, a roar came from the back of the crowd.  Apparently, the dwarves had found an untapped keg.  The gnomes were busy elsewhere setting up their fireworks for the end of the festival.  He smiled.  While the dwarves and gnomes were never considered the equals of the elves, they were dependable and friendly.  He took a deep breath and his smile vanished.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Ikeya, step forward,&quot; he said.  Ikeya hadn't taken on his family's name, or a surname of his own.  For hundreds of years he had been known simply as Ikeya.  Some people said he had taken on a surname for brief periods of time, but he often discarded them.  When asked as to why he did this, he only responded that his name was not important, only his faith.  Thex took another breath.  &quot;Ikeya,&quot; he said nodding at the Dal.<br>
<br>
&quot;King Thex,&quot; Ikeya replied matter-of-factly.  His voice was calm, indifferent.  He did not pledge his loyalty to Thex or Tunare.  The only respect Thex got out of him was his title.  Thex began to sweat.  Now it was going to get interesting.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ikeya, I know your answer,&quot; he began.  He raised a hand to stop Ikeya from speaking.  &quot;I did not call you forward to attempt to convert you.  I have called you forward so that you may be punished for your actions,&quot; he continued.  Ikeya's eyes blazed with anger for a moment, but the flame was quickly subdued.  &quot;The punishment for your crime is exile,&quot; Thex declared.  The crowd was silent.  Dwarves had put down their glasses, gnomes stood like statues, their fireworks forgotten.  The other elves were overcome with shock.  &quot;Have you anything to say?&quot; Thex finished.  <br>
<br>
Ikeya’s eyes flickered as he sorted through his countless memories, recalling his crime.<br>
<br>
--<br>
<br>
“I don’t understand this obsession you have with Solusek Ro.  What is it that drives you toward him?” a paladin asked him, setting his wineglass back on the table.<br>
<br>
Ikeya swirled his goblet idly as he considered the question.  <br>
<br>
“Well… For one thing, he is the patron deity of wizards.  And his doctrine puts an emphasis on power.  Something everyone strives for.  The more power one has, the better off one is.  Why deny the truth?  Solusek Ro is power.”<br>
<br>
The paladin gave him a puzzled look.  <br>
<br>
“That’s absurd.  You realize you are claiming loyalty to the god who scorched the Elddar Forest and destroyed the Tunarian Empire!”<br>
<br>
“What better display of power is there,” Ikeya replied, smiling at the paladin, “than to set ablaze one of the mightiest creations of the Mother of All?”<br>
<br>
The paladin began coughing violently.  Ikeya smirked at him.  He must have choked on his wine.  The paladin finally recovered himself and look up at Ikeya, his eyes seething with contempt.  <br>
<br>
“The power of creation is infinitely greater than destruction,” the paladin said, his voice reflecting the contempt in his eyes.<br>
<br>
“Ah… another blind follower of Tunare it seems.  The Mother of All will never rival The Burning Prince.”<br>
<br>
The paladin stood up suddenly, grabbing a hold of Ikeya by the cuff of his robe.  <br>
<br>
“Arrogant brat!” he shouted, throwing Ikeya into the wall.  “It’s pathetic excuses for Dal like you that will be downfall of our kind.”  The paladin punched Ikeya across the face, sending Ikeya to the floor.  The paladin staggered over to the fallen mass that was Ikeya and kicked him in the chest.  Ikeya gasped as the air rushed out of his lungs.  He moaned in agony.  The paladin picked Ikeya up by the back of his robe before knocking him to the ground with another punch.  Ikeya rolled onto his back and began to crawl back away from the paladin.<br>
<br>
“Are you mad?!  For the sake of Faydwer, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>think</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Does a paladin of Tunare assault a fellow Dal for stating his belief?  Are you drunk with pride?” Ikeya shouted, as best he could with his pained breath.  The paladin ignored him and continued to advance on the retreating Koada’Dal until he was standing over him.  Once more, he picked Ikeya up by his robe.  <br>
<br>
“So be it…” Ikeya whispered.  <br>
<br>
He lifted up his arms and grabbed onto the paladin’s wrists.  A fire ignited around his hands, encompassing them and the paladin’s forearms in flame.  The flames quickly spread until the paladin was engulfed in them.  The paladin released Ikeya and shouted in agony, twisting and turning wildly, trying to find anything to smother the fire.  In foolish panic, bystanders began throwing their drinks on the paladin, vainly attempting to put out the fire. But the alcohol only fed the blaze and left burning puddles on the ground.<br>
<br>
The paladin dropped to his knees before falling to the floor, the pain becoming unbearable.  Then as quickly as the flames had encompassed the paladin, they faded.  Only a charred corpse remained.<br>
<br>
--<br>
<br>
Ikeya's eyes blazed as he stepped backward.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Fool!&quot; he roared.  &quot;Foolish crusaders of Tunare!&quot; he shouted.  &quot;You will suffer! You will all suffer!&quot;  Even as the nearby guards stepped towards him in alarm, there was a thunderous crack that knocked down those nearby, and sent the audience scattering into the nearby forest.  A sword of flame appeared in Ikeya’s hand as he marched towards the dazed king.<br>
<br>
Ikeya’s advance halted abruptly as a silver blade slid itself gently across his throat.  He could sense nature’s power emanating from the metal.  <br>
<br>
“Firiona Vie,” Ikeya greeted the elf princess, without moving.<br>
<br>
“Extinguish it,” Firiona commanded.  <br>
<br>
Ikeya smiled as the silver blade pressed harder against his throat, threatening to slit it open.  He dropped his blade of flame and quickly stepped backwards.  The blade began to spin as it fell.<br>
<br>
“Xuzl,” Ikeya muttered.  The flaming blade’s fall came under control.  The blade whipped upwards and slashed towards Firiona.  Firiona lifted her blade and batted the flaming sword aside.  The sword of fire corrected its course and came back at Firiona, dancing in a brilliant display.  Firiona’s blade shifted left and right, blocking each swing the sword made, scattering sparks and wisps of flame in every direction.  Firiona gritted her teeth.  She just had to hold out long enough for the magic empowering the blade to depart, or for Ikeya to lose his concentration.  She wasn’t sure how long either of those would take.<br>
<br>
--<br>
<br>
Whizbang sat up, shaking his head.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>What just happened?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> he thought.  He stood up, gaining a few inches in height.  Whizbang was a gnome who had a reputation among his peers for making inventions that didn’t always function correctly.  He brushed off his tunic and looked around.  Most of the audience near the platform was still on the ground, or struggling to their feet.  Groans and moans echoed throughout the forest.  He tried to recall what had happened before he hit the ground.  There was a heretic.  The heretic was going to be punished for something.  Then the heretic… exploded?  That was a very odd punishment.  But then again, the elves were odd creatures.  He glanced toward where the heretic had been standing.  His eyes fell upon a sword of fire twirling around a woman he recognized as the Koada’Dal princess; the king was still sprawled on the ground in a daze.  Beyond the princess, the heretic stood unchallenged, his hands and fingers gesturing, ordering the blade where to strike next.  <br>
<br>
The gnome’s hands began to feel around frantically for his staff.  He had to help the princess.  Instead, his hand came to rest upon one of the fireworks the gnomes had brought.  He scrambled around and oriented it to face the accused.  While it wasn’t any powerful magic, it would have to do.<br>
<br>
--<br>
<br>
Firiona gritted her teeth as she fought the blade.  She tried to keep it in front of her, but all too often it would slip behind her and try to strike from behind.<br>
<br>
“Foolish girl,” Ikeya spat through teeth gritted in concentration.  “You all pledge your blind loyalty to Tunare, the ‘goddess of creation.’  Bah!  It was in fire that Norrath was created. Fire shaped the world.  The might of Fennin and Solusek Ro created Norrath, not your precious Tunare.  It was in fire that this world was born and in fire it shall be consumed!”  <br>
<br>
Small orbs of flame began to appear around him.  He hurled them casually at Firiona.  Firiona rolled behind a tree, the orbs exploding as they slammed into the trunk, setting it aflame.  She rolled again and lifted her blade upwards and blocked the Xuzl sword from splitting her in half.  <br>
<br>
Suddenly, there was a loud crack, followed by a loud, shrill whistling sound.  Firiona heard Ikeya bark a curse.  His bombardment of her ceased and the sword of fire vanished; the only remaining hints of its existence were smoke vapors.  She glanced over at Ikeya.  He was on the ground, a small object sticking out of his arm, where his skin was badly burned.  He was moaning.  Firiona looked around.  Her gaze fell upon a gnome who was holding the launcher of a gnomish firework.  She smiled at him and returned her attention to Ikeya.  Two paladins were “helping” him to his feet.  Ikeya grunted whenever the paladins roughly jostled him.<br>
<br>
“Throw him in the prison.  We can decide his punishment later.  Right now, we have to help these people,” Firiona ordered.  The paladin on Ikeya’s left nodded and brought the hilt of his sword down on the back of Ikeya’s skull.  The last thing Ikeya saw before the darkness overtook him were the marble walls of Felwithe.<br>
<br>
--<br>
<br>
Mirxa’s gaze focused on the elf in the cell.  His skin was pale, even by Koada’Dal standards.  He was of average height and build.  He sat with his back against the wall; his eyes were facing the floor.  His white hair was in disarray. Mirxa gasped and jumped back as the elf looked up at her.  She couldn’t see his eyes; they were hidden behind the shadows of the cell.  <br>
<br>
“Have you come to strip me of my mana today, enchantress?” he hissed.  <br>
<br>
Mirxa found herself seeking her voice to answer, but she couldn’t find it.  The elf’s voice was so full of contempt that she could not bring herself to respond to his question.  She inhaled a deep, steadying breath and began to chant.  Slowly, a blue aura began to pulse around the elf and strands of mana began to leak from his body into the air.  They collected into a ball before dropping into a vial Mirxa held.  She capped the vial, trapping the magical essence and left the room, twitching with guilt.  She cast her gaze on the floor as she ascended the twisting staircase that led out of the prison.  Her thoughts were elsewhere and didn’t notice the other elf until she bumped into him.  As she stumbled back, she caught sight of who she ran into.  The elf was dressed in royal clothes, and two armored hands were steadying him.<br>
<br>
“Your pardon, my lord,” Mirax begged.  By embarrassing chance, she had managed to run headlong into Tearis Thex.  He simply smiled forgivingly at her.  She bowed her head and hurried up the steps past him.  <br>
<br>
Tearis continued down the steps, until he arrived at Ikeya’s cell.  He nodded to one of his escorts, who promptly opened the cell door.  Thex strode in and came to a stop, towering over Ikeya.<br>
<br>
“What has happened to you?” Thex asked, addressing Ikeya in a concerned, sympathetic tone.<br>
<br>
Ikeya looked up at him.  He smiled faintly.  <br>
<br>
“Nothing has happened to me, dear Thex.  I am who I have always been,” Ikeya replied with a falsely amiable tone.<br>
<br>
“You aren’t Ikeya.  Who are you?” Tearis demanded.  “Ikeya would have never have done what you did.”<br>
<br>
A faint flame danced in Ikeya’s eyes.  <br>
<br>
