He gave a wide, horizontal swipe with it, two flames falling from it.  They touched the ground and immediately erupted into twin pillars, cascading towards Thex.  Charred dirt was thrown from the ground by the erupting flames.  Thex murmured an ancient Tunarian enchantment and his blade erupted in shimmering fire of its own.  He now wielded the Fiery Avenger.  He caught the two pillars on his blade and was pushed backwards by the force driving the inferno, but the pillars themselves were quickly dispelled after contacting the blade.<br>
<br>
Thex charged Ikeya, his blade held in a position where he could easily shift to block any more attacks.  Ikeya lifted his staff into the air and then brought it down, parallel to the earth.  Earth was once again thrown into the air as an invisible force was launched from the staff.  It slammed into Thex, barely weakened by the magic of the Fiery Avenger.  Thex heard and felt several bones snap under the pressure of the shockwave.  Pain flooded his mind and he could see Ikeya as if he was standing in a dark fog.  Thex couldn’t tell if Ikeya had indeed summoned a fog or if the pain was blurring his vision.  He slowly became aware that was he on the ground, resting against the distant palace wall.  Ikeya walked towards his, the sound of his staff tapping the narrow tile that formed a walkway was echoing.  Ikeya made another gesture with his staff.  Thex felt himself being lifted into the air by an unseen force.  Ikeya’s eyes burned with an unquenchable rage.  <br>
<br>
“I want your faith,” he said again.<br>
<br>
Thex felt himself getting warmer.  At first, it seemed pleasant compared to the chilling rain.  However, the temperature rapidly increased and Thex was soon screaming in pain as his armor channeled the heat directly to his skin.<br>
<br>
“Father!” a voice shouted.  Thex fell to the earth as Ikeya lost his concentration and turned to face the newcomer: Firiona Vie, her blade drawn.  Her gaze was fixed upon Ikeya, hatred burning in her eyes.<br>
<br>
“Ah, Princess,” Ikeya greeted.  “How fitting.  The king and the princess shall both burn in the same night.”  Flames suddenly danced in the air and a sword formed.  Ikeya grabbed it with his free hand and charged the princess.  Firiona lifted her blade.  Ikeya was no master swordsman, and his flaming weapon was swatted from his hand as he attempted to cut the princess in two.  Firiona took a step forward, pushing Ikeya down.<br>
<br>
She leveled the tip the blade to his throat, murder in her eyes.  <br>
<br>
“I will stop you,” she whispered, drawing her sword back in preparation to impale the rogue wizard.<br>
<br>
Ikeya’s eyes burned.  He pushed his staff forward, a lightning bolt arcing from it and slamming into Firiona.  Firiona skidded across the floor, screaming in agony, sparks still arching across her pale figure.  <br>
<br>
“Neither you nor anyone else can stop me!” Ikeya roared.  His feet left the floor as he floated up into the air.  He gripped his staff in front of him with both hands, closed his eyes, and began to chant.  A ring of flame spread out on the floor, twisting upward into the sky to meet a similar ring above Ikeya’s head.  Soon, the entire palace would be gone, burned to ashes.<br>
<br>
“Ikeya!” a third voice interjected.  Ikeya’s eyes snapped open to see a ball of ice cascading through the air towards him.  He had no chance to counter it, no chance to prepare a barrier, no chance to do anything but roar in impotent rage.  The ice ball slammed into him, knocking him to the floor.  The last thing in Ikeya’s vision before an icy darkness overtook his sight was a gnome.  Whizbang Dustyboots.<br>
<br>
Whizbang smiled grimly to himself, glad he had taken up the king’s offer to stay in the palace.  Had he refused the king’s hospitality, the Elven Empire would be in ruins.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Leave to a gnome to get the job done,</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Whizbang thought contentedly.<br>
<br>
--<br>
<br>
Ikeya awoke to the sounds of waves lapping against the shore, the sour scent of fish in the air.  He groaned as he stood up.  He immediately wished he hadn’t awoken.  There, standing along the pier and the beach head were dwarves, elves, and gnomes.  Before him was Tearis Thex, Firiona Vie, the gnome who had caught him by surprise, and a large cluster of guards.  His hands were bound.  He could barely wiggle his fingers, let alone make any gestures needed to cast a spell.  To his side was Jather.<br>
<br>
Jather had been found in the middle of the Faydark forest, forming incoherent sentences and pleading for forgiveness.<br>
<br>
“You are to be exiled,” Tearis said.  “Now go,” he said, pointing behind Ikeya.  Ikeya glared at Thex one last time, as if it could burn the elf down where he stood.  He turned his back on the king and walked down a line of dwarven guards towards a boat that was waiting for him.  Guards infested it as well.  As Ikeya stepped onto the boat, a belated regret overwhelmed him.  He knew he would never be able to step foot inside his home ever again.<br>
<br>
--<br>
<br>
The boat slipped out of view, and with it, the threat to Faydwer.  The army of Mistmoore had been defeated.  The fanatic exiled.  Once again, the land of the elves was in peace.  The sun set below the horizon and Thex breathed a sigh of relief.  It was over at last.<br>
